div.div: Anyway, sorry for wasting your time

Alacritty by default will inherit the working directory from its parent. No arguments required.
Oh, I misunderstood you, sorry. From my understanding, if I'm cded into Desktop in VScode and I type alacrity, alacrity should open in the desktop directory? It doesn't, it just goes to my predefined working_directory in my config, which is only there so it doesn't spawn in the system32 folder on windows as it usually does without it.
Not for me at least. I just typed alacritty --working-directory and it says a value is required. Ideas?

On any sane operating system that would be the default behavior anyways. And I don't see much problem in the way you do it right now.
OK, I completely understand. The only thing I wanted to achieve was saving a bit of time, but I understand. Maybe something so it default to the current working directory if no argument is provided to working directory? I don't know. Sorry for any trouble
